node.title: US Secretary of State orders probe into 'Havana Syndrome'
node.description: The US State Department has named a new coordinator for its investigation into cases of so-called Havana Syndrome, responding to increased pressure to investigate and respond to hundreds of brain injuries reported by diplomats and intelligence officers.

node.title: A Woke-Up Call for Democrats
node.description: Out of chaos comes just more chaos.

node.title: COP26 Protesters Back an Array of Causes, Connected by Climate Change
node.description: Thousands gathered in the rain in Glasgow to press the case for more urgent and meaningful action by world leaders in response to global warming.

node.title: Russia Hits Record Daily COVID Cases Despite Enforced Holiday to Curb Disease
node.description: President Vladimir Putin declared a holiday from October 30 to November 7 but the infection numbers continue to rise.

node.title: GOP Rep. Adam Kinzinger Mocks Marjorie Taylor Greene for Calling Infrastructure Communism
node.description: "Eisenhower's interstate system should be torn up or else the commies will be able to conveniently drive!" the Ilinois Republican congressman quipped.

node.title: Professors Sue University After Being Barred From Testifying Against DeSantis Voting Law
node.description: In a reversal Friday, the University of Florida announced that it would allow the professors to provide testimony as long as they did so on their own time and without using school resources.

node.title: High Schoolers Barred From Hockey Games After Crudely Taunting a Goalie
node.description: After students at a Pennsylvania high school yelled sexually explicit chants at a visiting team’s only female player, the entire student body was barred from games for the rest of the season.

node.title: Aaron Rodgers says he is unvaccinated and takes ivermectin
node.description: Rodgers, 37, lashed out at the media, the NFL's rules on COVID-19 testing and said he consulted with podcaster Joe Rogan for alternatives to the vaccine.

node.title: What Do You Want to Know About Kids and Vaccines?
node.description: The Times is hosting a live chat with a pediatric infectious disease specialist and two reporters about the coronavirus vaccine and children. We’d like to hear your questions.

node.title: Costa Rica moves to require Covid shots for children.
node.description: The Central American nation’s health ministry said on Friday it was adding Covid-19 to the list of required vaccinations for people 18 and younger.

node.title: Fire in Covid intensive care ward kills 11 people in India.
node.description: Staff at the hospital in the western state of Maharashtra tried to douse the fire with fire extinguishers, but the flames spread quickly in the airtight room.

node.title: Facing a spike in infections, Austria sharpens the rules of its Covid pass.
node.description: Austrians will need proof of vaccination or a past infection to be seated at a restaurant, enter a bar, visit a hairdresser or join any gathering of more than 25 people.

node.title: Baby Seals, Like Humans, Can Change the Tone of Their Voice
node.description: A new study offers clues about why human beings are so talkative.

node.title: Social media messages link suspects to Iowa teacher's murder, police say
node.description: Two 16-year-olds have been charged with murder in the first degree and conspiracy to commit homicide.

node.title: Infrastructure Bill Makes First Major U.S. Investment in Climate Resilience
node.description: The measure includes $47 billion to help communities prepare for the new age of extreme fires, floods, storms and droughts that scientists say are worsened by human-caused climate change.

node.title: NASA shuffles order of space station launch and landing after delays
node.description: NASA shuffles the order of a space station launch and landing after multiple delays.

node.title: Iowa students accused of killing high school Spanish teacher
node.description: Nohema Graber had been reported missing several hours before her body was discovered in a nearby park.

node.title: Mother Urges Parents to Vaccinate Children After 10-Year-Old Son Nearly Dies of COVID
node.description: "He wanted it previously," Jennifer Andersen, the child's mother, said of the vaccine. "He said, 'I wish I could have had that, and I probably wouldn't be like this right now.'"

node.title: Oil tanker explosion kills at least 92 in Sierra Leone
node.description: The explosion took place after a bus struck the tanker. Large crowds then gathered to collect leaking fuel.

node.title: After a Rough Year, New York Road Runners Searches for a Leader and Mission
node.description: After the coronavirus pandemic halted the club’s marquee events, the organizers of the New York City Marathon began trying to reclaim their roots and reconnect with the local community.

node.title: Spanish Police Seek Missing Plane Passengers After Emergency Landing
node.description: About 20 people fled a Moroccan flight that diverted to Mallorca after a passenger apparently fell ill. Some remained at large.

node.title: Lights Out: 5 New ‘Dark-Sky Places’ for Top-Shelf Stargazing
node.description: The International Dark-Sky Association awards certifications to sites with exceptionally high-quality night skies, including national parks, sanctuaries and reserves.

node.title: Prehistoric Teeth Could Be the Key to Dating 'World's Oldest Modern Human'
node.description: Recently discovered remains could take modern humans back more than 300,000 years.

node.title: More than 90 people killed by fuel truck explosion in Sierra Leone
node.description: A fuel tanker explodes near Sierra Leone's capital, killing at least 92 people and severely injuring dozens of others, after large crowds gathered to collect leaking fuel.

node.title: Flash flooding and hail as dangerous storms lash South Australia
node.description: The worst of the thunderstorms developed around Whyalla before tracking across the state's Mid North and into the Riverland, causing blackouts to large parts of the state.

node.title: Watch Live: Biden speaks after House sends infrastructure bill to his desk
node.description: The House also approved a rule on the Build Back Better bill that will allow for a vote on that bill later this month.

node.title: 8 dead after crowd surge at music festival in Houston
node.description: The "mass casualty incident" occurred after 9 p.m. Friday night when a crowd began to "compress" toward the front of the stage, authorities said.

node.title: For Carli Lloyd, Creative Tributes Abound as Retirement Approaches
node.description: The soccer star’s hometown gave a party in her honor, her employers moved a home game to a different state, and her teammates have been wearing her jersey number.

node.title: An Environmental Hero or Outlaw? Can It Be Both?
node.description: Steven Donziger, who won a $9.5 billion settlement against Chevron over dumped oil, began serving a six-month sentence for contempt of court last week.

node.title: VIDEO: Giant Anaconda Got Stuck in the Jungle After Swallowing Its Prey Whole
node.description: Officers freed the huge snake, but its belly was so bloated it could only float on the river.

node.title: CBS News poll: Are analog clocks on the way out?
node.description: Seven in 10 have at least one analog in their home, but just over half of adults under 35 have one.

node.title: How Slowing Down Helped Marathoner Molly Seidel Speed Up
node.description: The American runner says she owes her Olympic bronze medal to her coach, Jon Green, who turned her training approach upside down. New York’s 26.2 miles could be her toughest challenge yet.

node.title: Weed Helped Man Who Hated Exercise Become Ultra-Marathon Runner
node.description: In his new book "Runner's High," Josiah Hesse delves into the subculture of amateur and elite athletes who use cannabis for exercise.

node.title: Jim Jones Had a Twisted Idea of 'Revolutionary Suicide'
node.description: Jim Jones appropriated the idea of 'Revolutionary Suicide' - the risks of fighting oppression - and turned into a murderous notion designed to induce total loyalty.
